ombined avant-garde aesthetics and a deep preoccupation with the human condition, creating a model of politically engaged art in part through transcultural dialogues with Russian literary models. This study explores the deep connection between Spanish and Russian narratives immediately before and during the Second Republic, as well as themes as relevant today as nearly a century ago: the ethics of war, the newwoman, and responses to machine culture in the modern age. Lynn C. Purkey is an Associate Professor of Spanish at the University of Tennessee at Chattanooga.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRussian literaturexAppreciationzSpain. 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSoviet literaturexAppreciationzSpain. 0aSoviet literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782041078423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782041078/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles